  <glossary-entry>
    <heading>
      <greek-lemma>αἴθυια</greek-lemma>
      <transliteration>(aithyia)</transliteration>.
      A poetic word, of uncertain or indefinite meaning.
    </heading>

    <decision>
      <confidence>Probably</confidence>
      <conclusion>a large Gull</conclusion>,
    </decision>

    e.g.
    <bird>
      <scientific-name>Larus marinus</scientific-name>, the <common-name>Black-backed Gull</common-name>,
      <modern-authority>Sundevall</modern-authority>,
      <reasoning comment="rare in Greece"/> or
    </bird>

    <bird>
      <scientific-name>L. argentatus</scientific-name>, the <common-name>Herring Gull</common-name>
      <modern-authority>Krüper</modern-authority>, the former being rare in Greece.
      <reasoning comment="abundant during the winter and breeds about the middle of April"/>
    </bird>

    <bird>
      <modern-authority>Netolicka</modern-authority>'s hypothesis of the
      <scientific-name>Merganser</scientific-name>
      <reasoning>
        Do not tally with
        <ancient-authority>
          Aristotle
          <citation normalized-ref="Aristotle, Historia Animalium 5. 9, 542b"/>
        </ancient-authority>
      </reasoning>
    </bird>

    and that of
    <bird>
      <modern-authority>Groshans</modern-authority> that it was a
      <common-name>Diver</common-name> or
      <reasoning comment="do not tally with Aristotle">
        <ancient-authority>
          <citation normalized-ref="Aristotle, Historia Animalium 5. 9, 542b"/>
        </ancient-authority>
      </reasoning>
    </bird>

    <bird>
      <common-name>Grebe</common-name>,
      <reasoning>
        do not tally with
        <ancient-authority>
          Aristotle
          <citation normalized-ref="Aristotle, Historia Animalium 5. 9, 542b"/>
        </ancient-authority>
      </reasoning>
    </bird>

    <bird>
      <modern-authority>Schneider</modern-authority>'s identification with
      <common-name>Skua</common-name>, <scientific-name>Lestris Parasiticus</scientific-name>
      <reasoning>
        fails inasmuch as the latter does not dive
        <modern-authority>(vide Buchholz, op.cit. pp. 112, 113)</modern-authority>
      </reasoning>
      <reasoning>nor does it breed in the Mediterranean</reasoning>.
    </bird>

    The Herring Gull is abundant during the winter and breeds about the middle of April:
    <bird>
      the <common-name>Common Tern</common-name> (<scientific-name>Sterna anglica</scientific-name>)
      <reasoning comment="same time as the Herring gull">
        lays about the same time
        (<modern-authority>Krüper</modern-authority>)
        but in the lagoons and not on the cliffs
      </reasoning>.
    </bird>

    <ancient-authority type="myth">
      <citation
        normalized-ref="Homer, Odyssey 5. 337; 5. 353"
