    <ancient-authority type="scientific">
      Arist.
      <citation normalized-ref="Aristotle, Historia Animalium 5. 9, 542b">
        H.A. v. 9, 542b
        "<translation>The aithyia, or diver, and the larus, or gull, lay their eggs on rocks bordering on the sea, two or three at a time; but the gull lays in the summer, and the diver at the beginning of spring, just after the winter solstice, and it broods over its eggs as birds do in general. And neither of these birds resorts to a hiding-place.</translation>"
        (<quotation>ἡ δʼ αἴθυια καὶ οἱ λάροι τίκτουσι μέν ἐν ταῖς περὶ θάλατταν πέτραις, τὸ μέν πλῆθος δύο ἢ τρία· ἀλλʼ ὁ μέν λάρος τοῦ θέρους, ἡ δʼ αἴθυια ἀρχομένου τοῦ ἔαρος...</quotation>)
      </citation>
    </ancient-authority>

